{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657414/1923102801/0113.xml":{"full_text":"10\nISatioii\u2019s Mills Co Employ\nMore Than 6,000,000 Workers\nCensus Bureau Finds Flour Plants Could\nFeed 200,000,000\u2014First Report of Kind\nTook Two Years Work\nBV HARDEN COLFAX.\nA measure of the nation's ability\nto produce manufactured Roods has just\nbeen completed by the census bureau\nafter two years of work. The grand\ntotal of possible output during a sin\ngle year is set down by the bureau\nat $74,123,930,736. The returns used\nin making up this total came from\n15t.194 manufacturing plants through\nout the country.\nIn addition, 1.214 plants with a\nknown output of about $1,500,000,000\nannually failed to submit maximum\noutput figures. It is reasonably certain\nthat had the figures from these plants\nbeen available, the grand total of\nAmerican factories to produce would\nhave been written in figures topping\nthe $76,000,000,000 mark. This means\nthat under ideal conditions of labor,\ntransportation and raw material sup\nply our factories are capable of turn\ning out annually finished products to\nthe value of about S7OO for every man,\nwoman and child in the country.\nAc Inal Figure* Taken.\nThe survey was made in connec\ntion with the 1921 census of manu\nfacture! s. showing what the plants\nactually turned out in finished prod\nucts during that year of business\ndepression. the totals show that\nAmerican factories produced in 1921\ngoods to the value of about $43,800.-\n000,000. That was a drop of more\nthan $18,000,000,000. or about 30 per\ncent from the banner year of 1919,\nwhen mills and factories were whir\nring under the stimulus of post-war\nInflation and prosperity.\nThese figures, never before an\nnounced, tell an accurate story of\nthe extent of the damage done by the\nstorm of readjustment as well as the\ncapacity of the nation\u2019s gigantic\nmanufacturing machinery. They are\nreplete with detail. They cover 350\nseparate manufacturing industries,\nwhich gave employment during the\nheight of the depression to more than\n*6.000,000 workers. They tell the story\nof each industry, showing the extent\nc<> which it was affected by the eco\nnomic change. They indicate that\nthe country's manufacturing plants,\nworking at the maximum, are ca\npable of furnishing employment to\nmore than 12.000,000 workers..\nCciihux Innovation.\nThe measure of possible produc\ntion is an innovation in census bu\nreau work. It was embodied in the\n1921 returns upon the recommenda\ntion of a committee of a conference\nof trade associations held in Wash\nington August 18, 1921, at the in\nstance of the National Association of\nManufacturers. -Secretary Hoover ap\nproved the proposal and directed the\ninclusion of the survey in> the cen\nsus bureau\u2019s work.\nAs a result of the work the busi\nness men of the country will s*oon be\nacquainted in detail, for the first\nBALDWIN, IN TARIFF\nMOVE.KBRITAIN\nBelieved He Will Submit Pro\ntection to Electorate Prior\nto Budget in 1924.\nBy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, October 27. \u2014The protec\ntionist kite flown at Plymouth by\nPrime Minister Stanley Baldwin and\nby Neville Chamberlain, chancellor of\nthe exchequer, has set political cir\ncles buzzing with speculation as to\nwhen the premier intends to sound\nthe opinion of the country on such\na radical departure from Great Brit\nain\u2019s established free trade policy.\nOpinion so far holds that an elec\ntion\u2014if there be one on this ques\ntion \u2014will be fixed for the early\nspring of 1924. before the budget is\nsubmitted to parliament. One rea\nson for the choice of this time is\nthat the budget is bound to be an\nunpopular one inasmuch as ft will\nnot, according to Mr. Chamberlain\u2019s\nrecent statement, provide for any re\nduction in taxation. The government\nwould not be likely to risk facing\nan electorate disgruntled by an un\npopular budget.\nOpinions differ as to the impression\nmade on the party delegates who\nlistened to the speeches at Plymouth,\nsome reports saying that they cre\nated much uneasiness, others that the\ndeclarations of the prime minister\nand the chancellor were well re\nceived. This divergence is sufficient\nly explained by the well known fact\nthat the conservative party is in no\nwise unanimous on the protection\nquestion.\nThe premier is scheduled to speak\nduring the coming week at Swansea\nand Manchester \u2014the latter being the\nhome of the free trade movement\nand it is assumed that he will take\nthe nation more fully into his confi\ndence on those occasions. He also\nis to speak at Glasgow next month\nwhen he will have opportunity of\nsounding opinion in Scotland.\nThe ministry will have a stiff row\nto hoe. for the whole forces of lib\neralism, as well as the cohorts of\nthe labor party will be arrayed\nagainst it, although whether all fac\ntions of the labor element will be\nfound in opposition is said to be\ndouWlful.\nSOUTHERN MEDICAL\nBODY TO MEET HERE\nSessions From November 12 to 15\nWill Be Held in Various\nHotels.\nThe Southern Medical Association is\nto hold its seventeenth annual meeting\nhere November 12 to 15. Sessions of\nvarious sections will meet in the New\nWillard, Washington, Raleigh. Shore\nham New Ebbitt and Burlington hotels.\nAt the New Willard, which will be gen\neral hotel headquarters, the sections on\nmedicine and pathology will meet as\nwell as the Southern Gastro-Enterolog-\nIcal Association and a conference on\nmedical education.\nSections on pediatrics, obstetrics, eye,\near, nose and throat, radiology and der\nmatology and syphilology will meet at\nthe Washington Hotel, while the section\non surgery and bone and Joint surgery\namfthe Southern States Association of\nRailway Surgeons will assemble at the\nRaleigh Hotel. i\nAt the Shoreham the sections on\nurology and neurology and psychiatry\nwin meet, and at the New Ebbitt Hotel\nthe section on public health and the\nnational malaria committee will meet.\nThe Southern Association of Anesthet\nists will hold its sessions at the Bur\nlington Hotel.\nPresident Coolidge and Mrs. Coolldge\nare to receive the delegates-.lnformally\nat 12:30 o\u2019clock, November 15.\nDr. Thomas A, Groover is general\nchairman of the Washington committee\non arrangements.\nFINANCIAL.\ntime, of the capacity of each of the\nmanufacturing industries under most\nfavorable conditions. The federal\ngovernment, also, is placed in pos\nj session of detailed Information of ai\ni most vital value in time of war.\nHeretofore it has been impossible to\nmeasure accurately what any Indus\ntry could accomplish in event of a\nsudden call to service. The govern\nmrnt knows now jusd what it can ex.\npect from every factory in the couu\ntry.\nlinminae Output Possible.\nBy individual industries- the re\nport discloses outstanding facts of\nwhose nature there had long been\nmuch difference of opinion and s-onu\ndispute. The 20,172 bakery estab\nllshments in the country, for Instance.\narc capable of turning out half as\nmuch bread and other products\ni again as they produced in 1921. The\ncanners place their ability to pro\nduee at more than $500,000,000 an\nnually, or slightly double their 1921\noutput. The bool and shoe factories\nmeasure their maximum possible out\nput at about $1,400,000,000 annually\u2014\nsufficient to furnish footgear to 150,-\nI 000.000 people..\nThe shops producing railroad cars\nare prepared to touch a limit of\nmore than $1,600,000,000 annually, or\nHearly one-tblrd more than they'pro\nduced in 1921. Makers of clothing\nfor men ami women are ready to\nproduce $3,000,000,000 worth of prod\nucts, or sufficient to provide com\nfortably for half as many more per\nsons as bought clothes in 1921.\nGotten goods manufacturers, 1,328 in\nnumber, by speeding up could pro\nduce one-third more, makers of elec\ntrical machinery and supplies nearly\n1 twice as much.\nMill* Can Feed 200,000,000 Persons.\nFlour mills can turn out flour\nsufficient to feed nearly 200.000,000\npersons. The nation's 9.013 foundries\nand machine shops are prepared to\nincrease their 1921 production. If\nthey work three shifts a day, by 125\nj per cent. The furniture factories,\n'by running at the maximum, could\ni add 60 per cent to the volume of\ni their products.\ni The iron and steel works and\nrolling mills of the country, back\nbone of industrial prosperity as well\nas wartime activity, say they could\nspeed up to two and one-half times\nj their 1921 production. The leather\nindustries could almost double theirs,\ni More than 9,000 lumber manufac\nturers asserted that, on the aver\nage. they could add two-thirds to\ntheir producing ability of two years\nago. Nearly 400 motor vehicle man\nufacturers, who were working at a\ngood profit even during the Hull\nj period.' assert that they cou\u2019d turn\nout almost two and one-hali\nas many cars as they did that year,\nf* And so the story goes throughout\ni the list of the 350 industries. The\nI figures have been sent to the gov-\nI ernment printing office, and within a\nshort time. It is expected, the detailed\nI Information will be available for gen-\nI eral distribution.\nSOVIET PARLEY HIT\nBY SNUB OF MID\nFailure of Minister to Return\nCall Bars Russian Envoy\nFrom Japan.\nBV CLIFFORD FOX.\nBy Cable to The Star and Chicago Daily Sews.\nCopyright, 1923.\nPEKING, October 27.\u2014Failure of\nJapanese Minister Yoshizawa to re\nturn the call of M. Leo Karakhan, so\nviet envoy, has upset the latter\u2019s\nplans for departure to Japan to ar\nrange the reopening of the Russia-\nJapanese conference. Failure to re\nturn the soviet envoy\u2019s call is tanta\nmount to a declaration that Tokio is\nunwilling to resume discussions with\nMoscow. Action of the Japanese min\nister has greatly chagrined the so\nviet mission, which planned to use the\nopening of negotiations with Japan\ni as leverage to Induce China to rec\nognize the Moscow government.' If\nYoshizawa had returned Karakhan\u2019s\ncall it would have meant his receiv\ning a passport to enter Japan.\nCoaftHioM Promised.\nKarakhan in his efforts to force\n1 China to recognize the Moscow gov\nernment promised. It is understood, to\n1 give China vast timber and mineral\nconcessions, but China refused to con\nsider these offers until the Sino-Rus\nsia negotiations are formally opened.\nKarakhan. however, stubbornly in\nsists he will not negotiate until the\nsoviet government is recognized.\nHe finally threatened, it is said, that\nunless the attitude of the Chinese gov\nernment is modified, to offer the timber\nand mineral concessions to Japan, be\ning convinced that Japan would be\nwilling to recognize his government\nwhen tendered these concessions.\nIt is anticipated that China will\nshortly invite Karakhan to either com\nmence negotiations or leave Peking. It\nis significant that his congratulations\nto Tsao Kun, China's new president,\nI were unofficially acknowledged.\nThreatening Red Movement.\nI Meanwhile thrtatenlng movement of\nI red troops toward Mongolia are report-\nI ed, with the object of stengthening\ni the occupation of outer Mongolia,\nI which means further border trouble.\nI China\u2019s border garrisons have been\nj strengthened, but the movement of red\ntroops toward the Chinese eastern rall\nway zone is regarded here as a threat\nI against those in control.\nThe railway management is under\nj the control of a board composed of\nI Chinese and \"white\u2019\u2019 Russians, the lat\nter placed there by French investors.\nGeneral Manager Ostroumoff, chief of\nthe Russian railway administration,\ndeclares the continued 111 treatment of\nChinese In Russian Siberia and Mon\ngolia by the reds and the refusal of\nthe Moscow government to discuss this\nsituation has brought relations be\ntween the two countries to a serious\npoint.\nPOLICEMAN TRIED.\nSchotter Charged With Being Un\nnecessarily Bough.\nPoliceman William Schotter of the\nsecond precinct was tried before a po\nlice trial board at the District building\nyesterday on the charge of having used\nunnecessary force in arresting Hugh C.\nIrey, a real estate man, for alleged vio\nlation of the parking regulations.\nThe testimony all revolved around the\nquestion of the manner In which Schot\nter took Mr. Irey to a patrol box. Schot\nter was represented by Attorney James\nF. O\u2019Shea. The trial board probably\nwill render Its decision early next week.\nt\nThe paper used in printing Bank\nof England notes is manufactured at\na special mill in Hampshire, where no\nworker is allowed to enter any part\nof the building other than the room\nwhere he is employed.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON. -U -C\u201e OCTOBER 28, 1923-PABT 6.\nRANGE OF MARKET AVERAGES\nia*\u00ab\u2014 i mi\n.yQUAR fQllAt. rQUAK. TQUAH. yQfiML FQUAB yQUkg. y Qfigg qL'At 1\nTi 2 ;io\nv.-h\nI\nIjrfir LEGEND* |N\u2018-\nJ\nU| j Itf]j \u00aba.ls j\n\nI .IUIII I\nThe chart above shows the high and low, by weeks. of forty representa\ntive stocks dealt in on the New York Stock Exchange, from tht? first week of\nJuly, 1921, up to and Including the week ending October 27, 19J3. Solid curve\nrepresents 20 industrials and outline curve 20 rails. Lower-sertlon indicates\nvolume of sales of all stocks. Averages used are those co|nplled by the\nWall Street Journal. Industrials made a new low for the year J 86.01) Friday,\nOctober 26. f\nThe Year 1923 to Date on the Washington\nStock Exchange.\nI p to \u00bb4 including Saturday. October 27, 1823.\nFurnished by W. B. Hibbs Co.. Hlbbs Building.\nSales. BONDS. Open. High. Low. Clos*.\n$20,000\u20140. and P. Tel. of Va. 5s 94 94 I 92 93%\n64.500 Washington Gas 6s 19014 103 100*4 100%\n4.000 Ana. and Pot. River ILR. 5s 87 87 87 87\n56.000 C. and P. Telephone Ist 5s 95% 98% 96 96\n187.500 Capital Traction Ist 5s 96** 98 92% 94\n9.000 City and Suburban Ry. Ist 55....... SO 80 80 80\n26.500 Georgetown Gas Light Ist 5s 90 90 86% s\u00bb\n3.000 Metropolitan R. U. Ist 5a 93 98 97 97\n51.000 Pot. Klee. Power Ist 5s 97 97*4 f 96 96\n146.000 Pot. Klee. Power cons. 06Va\n53.500 Pot. Klee. Power deb. 6\u00bb 100 100 I 99*4 99^\n09,600 \u2014Pot. Elec. Power gen. Cs 99% 100 99% 99%\n9.000 Wash., Balto. and Annap. Ist 6s 77% 77% 70 70%\n141.500 Wash. Gas Light gen. 5s 95*4 96 I 92% 93%\n274.000 Wash. Ry. and Klee. cons. 4s 73 73% 70 70%\n35.000 Wash. Uy. and Elec. gen. 6s 99% 100 99% 99%\n65,200\u2014Wash. Gas 7%s 103% 105 102% 103\n40,300 \u2014Pot. Elec. Power 7s 106% 107% 106 106%\n59,100 \u2014Pot. Elec. Po.wer 6s. 1953 101% 102 J 100 100\nI,soo\u2014Dist. of Col. Paper Mfg. 6s 80 80 80 80\n15.000 Riggs Realty (long) 6s 93 93% 92% 93\n4,600 \u2014Wash. Market Cold Storage 5s 95 95 j 95 95\n20.500 Wardman Park 6s 101 10l 99 100\nShares. STOCKS. I\n3.213 \u2014Capital Traction 103*4 104 9S 99%\n4,883 \u2014Washington Ga>s 58% 59% 48 48%\n406\u2014N. and W. Steamboat 205 220 205 209\n5.888 \u2014Wash. Ry. and Elec, com 70 72% f 61. 69\n6,403 \u2014Wash. Ry, and Elec, pfd 75 76% 70*4 72\n25\u2014Capital National Bank 226 226 i 225 225\n424\u2014Commercial National Bank 148% 149 140 141%\n96 \u2014District National Bank 171 173 165 168\n16\u2014Farm, and Mech. Nat. Bank 241% 241% f 239 239\n46\u2014Federal-Amerlcan Nat. Bank 185 195 185 190%\n27\u2014Liberty National Bank 130 133 130 132\n57\u2014Nat. Metropolitan Bank 237 250 237 247\n486\u2014Riggs National Bank 537 655 298% 299%\n352 \u2014Riggs National Bank rights 100 100 f 92*4 *9B\n587 \u2014Amer. Sec. and Trust....- 282% 326\n384 \u2014Continental Trust 91 91 I 90 90\n36 National Savings and Trust SlO 351 s 310 350%\n67\u2014Union Trust 143 158 143 158\n45 Wash. Loan and Trust 320% 351 320% 351\n324 \u2014Merchants\u2019 Bank and Trust 127 135 127 127%\n20 \u2014East Wash. Savings Bank 17% 19% 17% 19%\n20\u2014Sec. Sav. and Coni'! Bank 250 260 250 260\n20\u2014Washington Mechanics\u2019 30 30 30 30\n46 Firemen\u2019s Fire Insurance 17% 19% I 17% 18\n100 \u2014Columbia Title Insurance 6% 6%, 6% 6%\n41\u2014Real Estate Title Insurance 120 125 120 120\n1.457 \u2014Mergcnthaler Linotype 173 178%; 147 158\n1,794 \u2014Lanston Monotype 77% 80% 72% 74\n373\u2014Security Storage 230 246 230 246\n6?S\u2014Washington Market 40 45 j 38 38\nUNLISTED DEPARTMENT. 5\n60\u2014American Com. and Savings Bank... 12 12-12 IS\n80\u2014Banking Trust and Mortgage 10 10%J 10 10%\nS6o\u2014Citizens\u2019 Savings Bank 12 12 11% 18\n37 Departmental Bank 7% 7% 6 6%\nB\u2014Munsey Trust 100 102 100 102\n200\u2014Northeast Savings 15 15 13 15\n46 \u2014Dist. Title Insurance 15 15 15 15\n76\u2014Wash. Title Insurance 5 7 j 5 7\nCash.\nHOW POOR MAN CAN CET AHEAIT\nTrue Stories of Wage Earners and Salaried! Men and\nWomen Who Have Found the Road to\nFinancial Independence.\nBy Samuel O. Rice, Educational Director,\nInvestment Bankers\u2019 Association of America I\na\n(This is the eighth of a aeries of twelve\nstories of wage earners and salaried men and\nwomen who have found the road- to financial\nindependence. The next one nidi tppetr\ntomorrow\u2019s Stir.)\nIn an automobile repair shop of a\nlarge nationally known corpor\u00a3tion\nIs' a young mechanic who, without\nfinancial training or much of an\neducation, combines admirably sound\nspeculation and safe Investments. He\nowns a little stock In the good com\npaliy that employes him and Is buy\ning more. That la sound speculation\nand commendable. It Isn't an invest\nment, for always the bond holders\nand other creditors come before\nstockholders and In event of drastic\nbusiness depression a sound, well\nmanaged business may cease paying\ndividends for awhile, although they\npay Interest on their bonds regularly.\nBut this mechanic sees dally how\nwell his department Is run. He\nknows It Is efficient and that there\nIs little waste or extravagance. He\nknows how the company treats Us\nemployes and some sense of its\npolicies trickles down from the main\noffice. He doesn't know absolutely\nthat this big business is profitable.\nHe Is not competent to Judge that;\nfew men are competent to correctly\nestimate the worth of any big busl-\nCURB STOCKS ADVANCE.\nSeveral New High Levels Are\nBeached During Week.\nNEW YORK, October 27.\u2014Important\nfeatures of the trading on the New\nYork Curb Exchange In the past week\nwere the displays of strength In a\nnumber of Industrial Issues, carrying\nsome of those stocks up to new high\nrecords and making them travel over\na wide range.' Parke Tllford was\ntraded in on the largest scale In the\nfirst half of the week, when it made\na gain of about 3 points to a new\nhigh record. There was steady ac\ncumulation of Hudson Company pre\nferred, which is expected soon to make\na distribution of *tn\u00ab revenues received\nfrom its aoldlpgs of pudfeon and Man\nness or the value ol Its securities.\nBut the mechanic knows his expert*\nence with the companl- Indicates that\nit is a fair, practical business. And\nso he bought its stoclc.\nThis stock happeijs to be quite\nactive on the stock exchange, a fact\nthat has led bucket 3)hops to try to\nInterest small investors in it, with\nthe purpose of \"switshlng\" them to\nsome worthless stocK later on. Had\nthe mechanic been employed in some\nother shop and knowri nothing of this\ncompany, except by hearsay, and had\na smooth bucket operator sold\nhim the same stock; he now holds\nhe would not have Ijeen speculating\nin the true sense of; the word. He\nwould have been gambling. He would\nhave been buying from a person\nabout whom he kne\\f nothing, a se\ncurity about which hjs knew nothing.\nThat is not speculating. It is gam\nbling. Securities should be bought\nonly from an established, reputable\nbroker or bond deajer, who knows\nand will tell the truth about them.\nThis mechanic considers his home\nan investment. It may decrease or\nincrease in value agd thus become\nspeculative, but in .the satisfaction\nand confidence it gires him and his\nwife, he figures that it is an invest\nment. It pays intefest in content\nment and in saving ;ent.\nhattan preferred. McCrory Stores fol\nlowed the declaration of an extra\ndividend with an advance of 11%'\npoints to 86%, and the B stock moved\nup more than 10 points to 74%.\nGillette Safety Raxor was in steady\ndemand and made a Sain of 3 points.\nAmerican Light and Traction, after\nbeing neglected for (some time, was\nalso in demand, advancing some 6\npoints to 121. Check er Cab was an\nother strong feature! making a gain\nof over 5 points to above 35, but\nother motor-stocks heavy. Ford\nMotor of Canada dropped more than\n20 points because of disappointment\nover dividend action. Motor\nmade a new low record.\nSomething ought to* be done to pre\nvent auto makers Q-om going inu\nthe gasoline busipesc Their bloomin'\ncare take\"too much- gasoljft as it Is.\nDISTRICT NATIONAL\nTO OPENNEW BANK\nAdditional Office Located on\nConnecticut Avenue\u2014Lo\ncal Securities Prices.\nUnder the authority of a permit is\nsued by former Controller of the Cur\nrency D. R. Crissinger last spring, the\nDistrict National Bank announces an\nadditional office in Washington, located\nal the corner of Connecticut avenue and\nK street, In the building which was re\nmodeled from the old Draper residence,\nwill be opened shortly.\nCol. Robert N. Harper, president of\nthe bank, yesterday said that lie had j\ndelayed the work on this olfice because i\nhe desired to await the promulgation of\nregulations by the controller on the J\nsubject of additional offices, which he\nhad understood were in process of for\nmulation.\nThe bank has signed a lease for the\nproperty on which the office will be lo\ncated. A spacious banking room and\nadequate vault facilities will be pro\nvided, in addition to an attractive la\ndies\u2019 banking room. Ample private\nparking facilities, which cannot at any\nhour of the day bo interfered with, will\nbe set aside for the exclusive use of the\nInstitution\u2019s customers.\n\u201cFull and unlimited accommodation 1\nwill be extended at the branch office\nboth to new and present patrons of the\nbank, but everything will be under the\ndirection of the officers and board of\ndirectors of the parent institution,\u201d Is\nthe comment of District Bank officials.\nI nlisted .Securities Price*.\nBONDS.\nBid. Akked.\nArmy and Nary Club 6s J 5\nContra* Club 4s 70\nCosmos Club \\K,a 75\nCity aub 7s r. 75 ....I\nMetropolitan Club 4%a 70\nSTOCKS.\nAnzcostlz Bank 165\nAmerican Com. A Savinas Bank 8\nBanking Truat Mortgage 10\nChapin-Hack* 8\u00bb pfd 75\nCitizens' Saving Bank 11%\nConnecticut Pie Co 135\nChristian Heuricb Brewery 65 85\nColumbia Hotel Co Sort 1000\nDepartmental Bank 6\nDistrict Title Ins. Co HI\n\u25a0exchange Bank 18\nKrznklln National Bank 140\nInternational Bank 135\nMiller Train Control t% 2%\nMnnsey Trust Co 104\nNorth Capitol Savings Bank 10\nNorthwest Savings Bauk 10\nNortheast Savings Bank 13\nPark Savings Bank 50\nPotomac Savings Hank 200\nStandard National Bauk 12\nWashington Title Ins. t> 5%\nWashington Base Ball Club 27\nMoody\u2019s Weekly Review.\nMoody's Weekly Review of finanial\nconditions in its current issue says, in\npart:\n\"Whether the Berlin government in\nview of the complete failure of its\nfiscal, financial and foreign policies for\nfive years can withstand the chagrin\nof tlte German people is a question\nwhich naturally should interest\nAmerica. But our foreign trade has\nalready discounted political chaos in\nEurope: and the worst that we seem\nlikely to suffer at the moment Is a\nfurther delay in the desired revival of\nthis trade.\n\"Yet stock prices are clinging tena\nciously to their recent low levels. It\nis usual in times like these for the\nstock market to hold firm through\nOctober owing to the supporting in\nfluence of the autumn trade; but this\nspecial trade activity terminates early\nin November. How well the stock\nmarket will hold In November in the\nabsence of the bracing influence of the\nfall trade is an open question.\n\"Rubber company stocks and bonds\nare suffering from the drastic compe\ntition which began about three years\nago. Tire shipments from January to\nAugust utterly failed to show the\nusual increase; and eight months' fig\nures indicate heavy overproduction.\nTires and other finished goods now\nbeing delivered are made of rubber\nwhich costs about 16 cents per pound\nmore than that used in 1922; and yet\nthe finished goods themselves are\nbringing about 17 cents per pound of\nrubber contents less than the goods\nsold last year. Thus the margin of\nprofit is badly reduced.\n\"if present trends, mercantile,\nfinancial and political, should persist\nfor a few month longer, we ought by\nnext spring or summer to have in\nhand pretty complete foundations for\nanother era of expansion In trade and\nin the stock and bond markets.\"\nCOCA-COLA BREAKS.\nWall Street Still Believes Coming\nDividend Safe.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, (jctoDer 27.\u2014A sharp\nbreak to a new Idw occurred in Coca-\nCola today and occasioned some doubt\nas to the safety of the 8* dividend.\nThe selling, however, was set down\nalmost entirely to professional attack\n\u2014the kind that has been responsible\nfor conspicuous weakness in first one\nspecialty stock after another recently.\nSo far as can be determined from the\nreports of Coca-Cola operations the\ncompany will show earnings of be\ntween $lO and sl4 per share on the\nstock In 1923.\nCoca-Cola is running into cheap\nsugar, it has approximately $3,000,000\ncash and owes nothing, and it is the\nopinion of people In close touch with\nthe company that the dividend will\ncontinue to be paid as long as con\nditions remain as they aer at pres\nnnt.\nBOND MARKET DULL.\nSaturday Trading Quiet With\nMany Buyers Absent.\nNEW YORK, October 27.\u2014Many\ntraders were absent from today\u2019s\nbrief and relatively dull bond market\nand prices drifted irregularly within\nnarrow limits.\nUnited States government bonds\nreceded some on limited offerings,\nprobably because the government was\nnot in the market. Recessions were\nslight. Foreign bonds were scarce,\nwith the result that a few of the Euro\n\u25a0pean and South American Issues\npointed upward.\nThere was a renewal of the demand\nfor railroad 4s and numerous high\ngrade railroad securities recorded\nmoderate gains. Buying of secon\ndary rails also overbalanced the of\nferings.\nTrading in industrial liens and pub\nlic utility issues was decidedly lim\nited. both classes falling off slightly\non a small turnover.\nTEN NEW PRODUCTION\nRECORDS SUMMARIZED\nNEW YORK. October 27.\u2014Ten\nproduction records that have been\nestablished in industry during the\nlast few months follow:\nLargest pig iron production.\nLargest cotton consumption.\nLargest steel ingot production.\nLargest crude oil production.\nLargest automobile and truck pro\nduction.\nLargest residential construction.\nLargest volume of mail order sales.\nLargest construction of locomotives.\nLargest volume of retail sales.\nLargest volume of railroad car\nloadings.\nImportant changes that have taken\nplace in the United States since the\npre-war of 1913 are:\nThe population of the United States\nhas increased 14,000,000 of people,\nwith their enlarged requirements.\nThe annual national income has in\ncreased from $34,000,000,000 to 150,-\n100,000,000.\nThe aggregate savings deposits\nfiave -Increased from $0,000,000,000 to\n$14,000,000,000.\nWHEAT ESTIMATES\nSEND PRICES OFF\nReports of Heavy Purchases in\nCanada for Sale in IT. S.\nWeakens Market.\nCHICAGO. October 27.\u2014Estimates\nthat 2,000,000 to 3,000.000 bushels of\nCanadian wheat, duty paid, had so far\nbeen bought to come into the United\nStates at 2 cents a bushel less than the\nprice of domestic grain of equal quality\nhad a bearish effect today on the wheat\nmarket here. Closing quotations were\nunsettled, %a% to %a% net lower, with\nDecember 1.06%a1.06% to 1.06% and\nMay 1.11%. Corn finished %a% to %a%\ncent down, oats at Va off to a shade\nadvance, and provisions unchanged to a\nsetback of 5 cents.\nMost of the Canadian wheat Imported\nInto the, United States up to this time\nis said to have been for mills, much of\nit to be ground into flour at various\nplaces east of Chicago. Besides, millers\nat Minneapolis and elsewhere northwest\nwere said to have purchased liberally\nfrom Canada in the last few days. Talk\nof increased competition from Russia\nin durum wheat was also given some\nnotice.\nEnlarged arrivals of new corn made\nthe corn market easier, despite unfa\nvorable weather. Rural offerings of oats\nwere scarce. Firmness of hog values\nupheld provisions.\n(MISTOCKSPOOR\nGUIDE TO HESS\nj\nReviewers Predict Sane,\nEven Operations With Few\nMoves Either Way.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YO&K, October 27\u2014In the\ndisparity between the depressed\ncharacter of the stock market and\nthe brisk condition of business in\ngeneral, there has grown up a dis\nposition to decline to accept the\nprophecy of evil in the mood of\nWall street. Reviewers who were\nquite sure we were in for a prolong\ned siege of depression are now assert\ning that the stock market is predict\ning nothing at all. In other words,\n|at a moment when the country turns\nto It for u whisper about the\nof trade, it says absolutely nothing.'\nBuiiatM on Sane Baals.\nBusiness has shown no tendency\nduring the last six days to enter\nupon a period of extraordinarily ac\ntive operations. The outlook now Is.\nas it has been, for a period of even,\nsane, sound business and nothing\nmore. It is not to be a time for a\nkilling. But on the other hand, no\nenterprise that is economically sound\nhas anything to fear from the months\nimmediately ahead.\nThere is some discussion to\nwhether buying power has declined.\nGrocery sales have fallen oft slightly\nand collections are also showing a\ntendency downward. The slackness\nIn collections Is probably a post va\ncation manifestation. Has buying\npower declined? It usually shows a\ndrop after the first rush of seasonal\nactivity at this time of the year.\nGerman Stocks Rise.\nThe occurrences In Europe have 1\nplayed so prominent a part in the.\nnews columns that they need not be j\nreferred to here. Two outstanding\nfacts in the industrial affairs of\nGermany may, however, be men\ntioned.\nFirst, while stocks have risen to\nridiculous proportions because of the\nrapid decline of the mark, they have\nactually risen substantially in terms\nof gold values. It Is now figured that\nthe gold prices of the stocks have\nactually gone up 100 per cent in a\nyear.\nThe second is that imports have\nfallen off in recent months, while\nboth imports and exports are less\nthan they were a year ago.\n(Copyright by V. P. C. News Service, Inc.)\nLIVE STOCK MARKETS.\nBALTIMORE, Md.. October 27 (Spe\ncial). \u2014The live cattle market con\ntinues quiet and values rule easy\nin buyers\u2019 favor under ample receipts\nat stockyards and a light demand\nwhich is centered on cattle of first\nquality.\nArrivals by boat mostly of ordinary\ngrade and slow to move out even at\nconcessions in price. Quotations to\nday at Light Street wharf:\nBeef cattle, first quality, pound, 7\nto 8. Medium, 5 to 6. Bulls, as to\nquality, 4 to 5. Cows, choice to fancy,\n5 to 6. Common to fair. 3to 4. Oxen,\nas to quality, 41's to 5%. Milk cows,\nchoice to fancy, head. 80.00 to 75.00.\nCommon to fair, 30.0(0 to 50.00. Calves,\nveal, choice, pound, 12 to 12%. Ordi\nnary to medium, 10 to IJ. Hough,\nheavy, common. 4 to 6. Sheep, choice,\n5 to 6. .Old bucks, 4 to 4%. Common,\n2 to 3. Lambs, spring, choice, 12 to\n13. Fair to good. 10 to 11. Common,\nthin, 8 to 9. Hogs, straight, 7 to 8.\nSows, 5 to 6. Stags and boars. 3 to 4.\nLive pigs, as to size and quality, 8 to\n9. Shoats, as to size and quality. 7\nto S.\nNEW YORK, October 27. \u2014Cattle re\nceipts none: steady. Steers. 5.00a9.30;\nstate bulls. 3.00a4.60; cows, 1.25&4.00.\nCalves \u2014Receipts, 76 head; steady.\nVeals, 14.50a15.50; culls and little\ncalves, 8.0Ga9.00; buttermilks and\ngrassers, 4.00a5.00.\nSheep and lambs \u2014Receipts, 25 head;\nsteady. Sheep, 5.00a6.00; culls, 2.00a\n3.00; lambs, 10.00al4.50; culls, 7.50a\n9.50.\nHogs\u2014Receipts none; steady. Light\nto medium weights, 7.50a7.75. Pigs,\n7.00a7.25: heavy bogs, 7.25a7.36;\nroughs, 5.75a6.25.\nNEW GOLD NOTES ISSUED.\nBERLIN, October 27.\u2014The first of\nthe new gold-loan nbtes were issued\ntoday, and the output continues. The\ntotal value of these notes to be pift\nin circulation, inclusive of certain\nothers, is not to exceed 600,000,000\ngold marks.\nMORE BUSINESS FAILURES.\nNEW YORK, October 27.\u2014Business\nfailure\u00ae reported to R. G. Dunn\nCo. this week show a considerable\nincrease, the total being 469. This\nIs 83 more than last week and 112\nmore than a year ago. All section*\nexcept the west report more defaults\n(han last week, and all of them show\na larger number than in this week\nof 1922. Canadian failures were 46,\ncompared with 50 last week.\nI The I\nMargin of Security\nWe Demand to Safeguard\nClients Investing in Our Jj\n7%\nPint Mortgage Note*\nlain re* absolute safety under any and alt\nconditions. v\nIt\nUpholds also our established record of\nnever having lost in either principal or\nInterest as mneb aa a single penny.\nGuaranteed titles and insurance policies\nfurnished with all notes.\nNotes of SIOO, $250. up to $5,000\nI Now on Hand\nFor full particulars apply to Ur.\nO'Donuell, Loan Department.\nCHAS. D. SAGER\nOS4 14th It.\u2019 H.W, 0\nMain M, Jj\nSUSPENSION STUNS\nFILMJAPITAL\nFamous Players\u2019 Action Hard\nFinancial Blow to Hun\ndreds of Employes.\nSpevial Dibpalch to The Star.\nLOS ANGELES, October 27.\u2014An- i\nnouncement of the zusponsion of pro-\nductlon activities at the big- Famous\nPlayers-Lasky studio until such time\nas production costs are brought down\nto a common sense level deals the\nmotion picture industry\u00a9! Hollywood\nthe hardest blow it has felt since it\nattained rank as the film capital of\nthe world.\nOs the 1,200 employes of this studio,\nonly a few high-salaried stars and di\nrectors. under long-term contracts,\nwill continue in the employ of the\ncompany. The others, many of them\nwell paid artisans and experts who\nhave been with the concern for a\nnumber of years, find themselves\nthrown out of work at only a few\ndays\u2019 notice, and by no means cer\ntain of re-employment when produc\ntion is resumed.\nHundreds Face Distress.\nIn addition to the regular pay roll\nemployes, hundreds of actors and ex\ntra people who have been accustomed\nto look to the big productions at the\nFamous Players-Lasky for almost\ncertain employment find themselves\nfacing a period of real distress\u2014a fu\nture that is almost hopeless.\nThe authorized announcement by\nMr. Lasky says that with the excep\ntion of the four companies now in\nproduction all activities will cease for\nten weeks, or until early in January,\nand that the studio contemplates a\nreorganizing in the meantime. Just\nw'hat that will mean to the employee\nwho are to be let out is not clear. .But\nit generally accepted as notice to\nall but a pitiful few who have been\nadvised otherwise that they had bet\nter look elsewhere for employment.\nInsiders Expected Blow.\nThis is the first time that the\nFamous Players, the most powerful\nof all motion picture organizations,\nhas had a complete suspension of ac\ntivities. The suspension, however,\ndid not come as a surprise to insiders.\nMounting costs of production, due\nlargely to needless extravagance and\nwaste, could not be checked. Some\nradical method had to be applied.\nAll Hollywood concerned In any\nway with the movies has been stun\nned by the blow. It is feared now\nthat other studios will suspend or\ncurtail production. Lean days are\nahead for actors and extra people\nwho depend upon chance employ\nment. and their number runs into the\nthousands. But, like the actors on\nBroadway, and the sparrows when\nthe snow covers the ground, they al\nways seem to find a living, and keep\nthe faith.\nMay Take Pay Reductions.\nPola Negri. Gloria Swanson and a\nscore of other high-salaried stars\nand directors, under contract, will\nnot be cut off at the pay window.\nBut do not imagine that they will not\nbe reasoned with\u2014-and most success\nfully in most cases. Most of them\nprobably will consent to have their\ncontracts moved forward so that they\nwill draw nothing during the work\nless period. Others may consent to\na reduction of salary.\nDRY GOODS STRONGER.\nGray Goods More Active\u2014Yams\nAlso Higher.\nNEW YORK, October 27.\u2014Cotton\ngoods markets were more active to\nday in the gray goods division. Bales\nof finished goods showed little\nchange. Yarns were higher and quiet.\nSilks were quiet, and a more hopeful\nattitude was shown toward spring\nopenings due to begin next month in\nthe larger houses. Men's wear was\nquiet, with dress goods and cloakings\nsteady. Burlaps showed little change.\nCOFFEE PBICES lOWER.\nNEW YORK, October 27.\u2014N0 im\nprovement has been reported in the\ndemand for copper and prices have\nbeen easier during the week. Ru\nmors of business below 12*4 cents for\nelectrolytic, delivered, have not been\ndefinitely confirmed, but it is be\nlieved that the metal is freely avail\nahle at that figure. Iron easy.\nI\nMONEY TO LOAN\nON\nDISTRICT OF COLUMBIA AND\nCHEVY CHASE, MD., RESIDENCES\nSy 2 Interest\nH. L. RUST COMPANY\n912 15TH STREET N.W. MAIN 6888\nLOAN CORRESPONDENT FOR THE PRUDENTIAL\nINSURANCE COMPANY OF AMERICA\nPatronage is very sensitive it usually goes only\nwhere it is urgently invited, and its sojourn is\nlimited to the character of its treatment\nOur Business Has Been Built\n\u2014not only upon this theory, but upon our ability to demonstrate\nthat degree of human interest in every customer which is so\nnecessary to his peace of mind where investments are involved.\nWe Invite You to Try Our Service\n\u2014by investing your funds in our\nF